Why R?

R is a programming language and free software environment for statistical computing and graphics supported by the R Foundation for Statistical Computing. The R language is widely used among statisticians and data miners for developing statistical software and data analysis. (from Wikipedia

Some pros

  • R is free
  • R has a great help system
  • R is multi-platform (Windows, GNU-Linux, MacOSX)
  • R has a lot of pre-installed statistical functions
  • The user can create and apply their own functions in R

Some cons - and our reply to them!

  • R has a limited graphical interface - but only when used in the command line!
  • It doesnt have commercial support for users - but we can check forums such as Stack Overflow!
  • It uses programming language and one has to learn the syntax - but were here to show you the basics!

Here are some great open source resources for your references:

  • R for Data Science
  • Advanced R
  • Fundamentals of Data Visualization
  • blogdown: Creating Websites with R Markdown

General tips for learning R programming

  • Google is your friend! All levels of programmers search the web for solutions to coding problems. As you continue to develope your R skills you will also develope an intuition to search for solutions faster.
  • Organize your data, images, scripts, and notebooks into separate directories. You have a lot of worry about the more organized you are better.
  • Comment your code! Try to consistenly write notes within your code to explain what your are doing and results. If you dont, you WILL forget when you come back to it in the future. Damn you past self!
  • Stay positive and have fun :)

Introduction to R programming language

Intro

When writing R code, using hashtags (#) to include comments is highly recommended to make the notes understandable. Example:

print("Hello") # This command prints an initial greeting :)
## [1] "Hello"

How to get help

? to read the help page of functions or data sets. For example:

?R.version

or

help(R.Version)

The RStudio cheatsheets are a great resource.

Also check Stack Overflow frequently :)

Object names

To assign an object to a name we use <- (equivalent to =). The typing shortcut is Cntr + -. Names

  • are case sensitive
  • can contain letters, numbers, . and _. They should start with a letter.
  • should not have function or operator names: function, if, c

Example:

Greeting <- "Hello"

Greeting
## [1] "Hello"

Data objects

There are the following types of objects:

  • Vectors
  • Factors. For qualitative data.
  • Lists. Can contain vectors of different types (integer, double, boolean).
  • Arrays. Vectors organised by rows and columns.
  • Data frames. Like an array but can contain columns of different types. The columns are called variables. A data frame is the most common way of storing data in R.

Some examples:

# Vectors
x <- c(8,2,5,6,7)
y <- c(34,23,67,65,23)
z <- c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, TRUE)

# Factors
a <- factor(c(1,2,3,4,5))
b <- factor(c("a", "b", "c", "d", "e"))

# Lists
l <- list(1:3, "a", c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE), c(2.3, 5.9))
l
## [[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "a"

## [[3]]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
## 
## [[4]]
## [1] 2.3 5.9
# The elements in a list can be named:
l_named <- list(int = 1:3, char = "a", bool = c(TRUE, FALSE, TRUE), dbl = c(2.3, 5.9))

num.data <- array(c(x, y, z), dim=c(5,3))

Basic maths and statistics in R

  • +, -, * and /
  • ^ and sqrt
  • exp, log, log10, log2, logb(x, base)
  • max, min, range, mean, median, var, sd, quantile, sum
  • Logical operators: <, <=, >, >=, == (equals), != (not equal to), && (and), || (or).
  • Logical clauses if() {} else {}.
  • Set operations: union(x, y), intersect(x, y)

Examples:

x^2
## [1] 64  4 25 36 49
x+y
## [1] 42 25 72 71 30
sum(x)
## [1] 28
mean(x)
## [1] 5.6
median(x)
## [1] 6
var(x)
## [1] 5.3
if(min(x)>1 && min(y)<10) {
  print("Yes")
} else {
  print("No")
}
## [1] "No"
if(min(x)>1 || min(y)<10) {
  print("Yes")
} else {
  print("No")
}

Subsetting strings and arrays

With the function c() we can generate strings of values. With the coordinates (square brackets, [ and ]) we can select specific elements from strings. With the operator $ we can access columns in a data frame by the variable name. For lists we can use the operators [ ], that will return a list, or [[ ]] that will return the elements of the list

You can find some help on subsetting here and here

Examples:

# Generate a vector of consecutive numbers:
g <- c(1:7)
g
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
# Generate vectors of repeated values:
h <- rep(4, 7)
h
## [1] 4 4 4 4 4 4 4
# Select specific elements from a vector
x
## [1] 8 2 5 6 7
x[2]
## [1] 2
x[c(2,4)]
## [1] 2 6
x[2:4]
## [1] 2 5 6
# Select specific elements from a list
l
## [[1]]
## [1] 1 2 3
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "a"
## 
## [[3]]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
## 
## [[4]]
## [1] 2.3 5.9
l[[3]]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
l_named
## $int
## [1] 1 2 3
## 
## $char
## [1] "a"
## 
## $bool
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
## 
## $dbl
## [1] 2.3 5.9
l_named[[3]]
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
l_named$bool # If we give names to the items in a list, we can access them like this.
## [1]  TRUE FALSE  TRUE
# Select specific elements from a matrix.
num.data
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    8   34    1
## [2,]    2   23    1
## [3,]    5   67    0

Generate random sequences

  • Check ?sample
sample(10)
##  [1]  3  9  8 10  1  2  6  5  4  7

## [1] 5 8 9 6

##  [1]  5  7  3 10  4  6  2  4  6  9
sample(x, prob=(x/sum(x)))
## [1] 5 6 8 7 2
  • Random distributions. In general, rDistribution generates a random distribution with a given sample size (first argument) and given parameters. Examples:
    • Normal distribution rnorm
    • Student \(t\) distribution rt
    • Poisson distribution rpois
    • \(\chi ^2\) distribution rchisq

To visualise it in a histogram:

hist(rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)) # 100 samples of mean=0 and SD=1 from a normal distribution.

Use dnorm for density at a value, pnorm for distribution function and qnorm for quantile function. Same for other distributions. Check the help pages for these functions if youre interested.

Dealing with NAs

Identifying and replacing non-available (NA) values in our datasets can be useful:

v <- c(1, 5, 19, 2, 23, NA, 3, 9, NA)
v
## [1]  1  5 19  2 23 NA  3  9 NA
is.na(v)
## [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
which(is.na(v))
## [1] 6 9
# Create a vector without the NAs
w <- v[!is.na(v)]
w
## [1]  1  5 19  2 23  3  9
# Substitute NAs for e.g. 0
v2 <- v
v2[is.na(v2)] <- 0
v2
## [1]  1  5 19  2 23  0  3  9  0
# Inf (infinite) and NaN (not a number) are different from NA:
5/0
## [1] Inf
0/0
## [1] NaN
is.infinite(5/0)
## [1] TRUE
is.nan(0/0)
## [1] TRUE
# NAs can be removed in some functions
mean(v)
## [1] NA
mean(v, na.rm=TRUE)
## [1] 8.857143

For linear models (lm function) one can use na.omit or na.exclude. ## Ordering & sorting

The function order orders the items in a data frame. By default it does it in increasing order, but we can specify the opposite with the parameter order(..., decreasing = TRUE). The output of the function is the position of the elements in the data frame, not their values.

my.data
##   X1 X2 X3
## a  8 34  1
## b  2 23  1
## c  5 67  0
## d  6 65  0
## e  7 23  1
order(my.data) 
##  [1] 13 14 11 12 15  2  3  4  5  1  7 10  6  9  8
order(my.data, decreasing = TRUE)
##  [1]  8  9  6  7 10  1  5  4  3  2 11 12 15 13 14

sort is used to order the elements in a vector:

v2
## [1]  1  5 19  2 23  0  3  9  0
sort(v2) # Orders the elements in a vector
## [1]  0  0  1  2  3  5  9 19 23
sort(my.letters, decreasing = T)
## [1] "f" "e" "d" "c" "b" "a"

sort doesnt work for data frames, but works with vectors within a data frame (i.e., variables):

my.data
##   X1 X2 X3
## a  8 34  1
## b  2 23  1
## c  5 67  0
## d  6 65  0
## e  7 23  1
sort(my.data$X1)
## [1] 2 5 6 7 8

Upload and Exporting

Importing data from Excel

To import a dataset from Excel the best is to save the Excel file as a comma-separated values (.csv) or a tab-separated values (.tsv) file.

The .csv and .tsv files can be imported from the tab Environment in RStudio:

Click on Import Dataset > From text (base)....

Alternatively, you can use the following command:

iris <- read.csv("data/iris.tsv", header = TRUE, sep = "\t")

Exporting data

iris_tail <- tail(iris)

# csv
write.csv(iris_tail, file = "data/iris_tail.csv", quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE)
## Warning in write.csv(iris_tail, file = "data/iris_tail.csv", quote =

# tsv
write.table(iris_tail, file = "data/iris_tail.tsv", sep = "\t", quote = FALSE, row.names = FALSE, col.names = TRUE)

Installing Packages

A package is file containing some functions designed for a specific task(s). For example, ggplot2 is very useful to create elegant plots and the package vegan is used for ecological analyses.

The package readxl is designed to deal with .xlsx files. One advantage is that it has functions that allow to read files with more than one spreadsheet.

To install a package and to activate it in the current workspace we do:

# To install a package (this task can take a while and may ask for additional packages to be installed):
install.packages("ggplot2")

# To call the package and use its functions in the current session use:
library(ggplot2) # or:
require(ggplot2)

Using the Bioconductor software to install packages is highly recommended:

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager"))
    install.packages("BiocManager")   # This command installs BiocManager if it is not already installed. 

BiocManager::install("ggplot2")

require(ggplot2)

Tidyverse packages

The Tidyverse packages are a modern set of functions that are based on the tidy tools manifesto by Hadley Wickham. Two of the prinicples in the manifesto that we believe are important for teaching R are:

  • Compose simple functions with the pipe
  • Designed for humans

We will show you how the Tidyverse tools maintain these priciples later.

There have been some hot debates about how to teach R to beginners. The point of contention is whether to teach students Base R first or go straight to the Tidyverse packages. David and I believe a balance is really import, so today we will show you both :)

Here are the tools we will be using today:

  • tibble: better data frames
  • dplyr: a fast, consistent tool for working with data frame like objects
  • readr: to import data from files
  • tidyr: data tidying and rearrangement

To load all these awesome packages at once, run this code

library(tidyverse)
##  Attaching packages  tidyverse 1.2.1

##  tibble  1.4.2      dplyr   0.7.8

##  readr   1.2.1      forcats 0.3.0
##  Conflicts  tidyverse_conflicts() 
##  dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()

# or you can load individual package

library(dplyr)
library(readr)

dplyr

The dplyr package allows you to interact with data frames and tibbles (a task most biologist will be doing). The package is easy to learn because it is based around using verbs to manipulate your data frames. In fact, dplyr is referred to as, the grammar of data manipulation. Here are the verbs we will learn about today:

  • Select(): return specific columns of a data frame
  • Filter(): extract rows of a data frame that meet specified conditions
  • Arrange(): order data by row (i.e.descending order)
  • Rename(): rename the title of a column
  • Mutate(): add a new column to your data frame
  • Summarise(): return summary statistics for your data frame
  • Group_by(): organizes data into specific groups

Here are some code examples!

Select()

# load the package
library(dplyr)

# Check out the iris dataset before and after converting it to a tibble!

Notice the %>% symbol, this is known as a pipe. You can think of it as piping the output of one command into another command. By structuring your code this way, it becomes closer to natural language!

The tibble and the %>% are two examples of how Tidyverse tools and packages use the principles:

  1. Compos simple functions with the pipe
  2. Designed for humans

Arrange()

This verb allows you to order your data by value or alphabetically

# Print iris and arrange the rows from smalled to longest Sepal.Length
iris %>% arrange(Sepal.Length)

Mutate()

This verb allows you to add new columns to your data frame

Lets that the ratio between Sepal.Length and Petal.Length is important for your study. You can add a column with this ratio by doing this:

iris %>% mutate(sep_to_ped_ratio = Sepal.Length/Petal.Length)

Summarise

This verb allow you to make summary statistics from your data

# Cacluate the mean Sepal.Length and how many observations there are
iris %>% summarise(avg_len = mean(Sepal.Length), n = n())
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##   avg_len     n
##     <dbl> <int>
## 1    5.84   150

Group_by()

This verb allows you to break up your data into groups. In the iris dataset there are multiple species, we many want to calculate statistics about the invidual species and not the whole dataset

# Group by species and calculate the mean Sepal.Width
iris %>% group_by(Species) %>% summarise(avg_sepal_w = mean(Sepal.Width))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   Species    avg_sepal_w
##   <fct>            <dbl>
## 1 setosa            3.43
## 2 versicolor        2.77
## 3 virginica         2.97
# Count how many observations there are per species
iris %>% group_by(Species) %>% count()
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##   Species        n
##   <fct>      <int>
## 1 setosa        50
## 2 versicolor    50
## 3 virginica     50

RStudio Projects

The objects created in a R session are shown in the tab Environment. These objects will not be available if we close the R session unless we save the workspace (however youre always asked if you want to save the current workspace upon closing R or RStudio).

A good alternative to not deal with this issue is to create a R project.

1. Click on Create a project.

Click on Import Dataset > From text (base)....

2. Associate your R project with a directory in your computer (New Directory or Existing Directory). Alternatively, you can download a repository from a version control platform like GitHub.

Click on Import Dataset > From text (base)....

3. Choose a name for your directory. You can also turn the directory into a git repository.

R markdown and R notebooks

Check the R markdown cheatsheet for markdown help.

In this section, lets open the file workshop_notebook.Rmd in RStudio and check it in parallel to the workshop_notebook.html file. We have created a R notebook (written in R markdown) that can be knitted to generate the html document.

The elements of an R Markdown are:

  • the header. This is where the title, author, date and output format is specified. Output format can be pdf, html, docx
  • the main text. It can include sections, bullet points, tables, etc. Sorry to repeat ourselves, but check the R markdown cheatsheet for more information :)
  • code chunks. To insert an R code chunk type Cntrl+Alt+I or go to the Inset tab in the script window in RStudio. The chunks work like tiny R scripts and you can also include comments inside using hashtags (#). Apart from R code, you can include chunks for other coding languages.
